{"PageNumber":20,"Angle":0,"RotatedAngle":0,"Height":1620,"Width":2880,"OriginHeight":0,"OriginWidth":0,"Elements":[{"Index":0,"Type":"Discard_type","Text":"#  AES – Key Expansion","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":211,"Y":308},"LeftTop":{"X":211,"Y":190},"RightBottom":{"X":1302,"Y":308},"RightTop":{"X":1302,"Y":190}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":1,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"● Let's say that we have the four words of the round key for the $i^{th}$ round: $w_i w_{i+1} w_{i+2} w_{i+3}$","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":222,"Y":639},"LeftTop":{"X":222,"Y":440},"RightBottom":{"X":2451,"Y":639},"RightTop":{"X":2451,"Y":440}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":2,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"● For these to serve as the round key for the $i^{th}$ round, i must be a multiple of 4","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":222,"Y":830},"LeftTop":{"X":222,"Y":648},"RightBottom":{"X":2437,"Y":830},"RightTop":{"X":2437,"Y":648}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":3,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"• These will obviously serve as the round key for the $(i/4)^{th}$ round","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":222,"Y":953},"LeftTop":{"X":222,"Y":859},"RightBottom":{"X":2420,"Y":953},"RightTop":{"X":2420,"Y":859}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":4,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"● For example, $w_4, w_5, w_6, w_7$ is the round key for round 1, the sequence of words $w_8, w_9, w_{10}, w_{11}$ the round key for round 2, and so on","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":329,"Y":1138},"LeftTop":{"X":329,"Y":972},"RightBottom":{"X":2512,"Y":1138},"RightTop":{"X":2512,"Y":972}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":5,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"● Now we need to determine the words $w_{i+4} w_{i+5} w_{i+6} w_{i+7}